Arduino Project Report
Frequency detector with 10-bit display
Sumit Ghosh*, Somanko Saha, Shalini Das and Bisweswar Sen
Group-3, Indian Institute of Science Education and Research, Pune
Report by - Sumit Ghosh
Roll No. 20201222
Course - Electronics I (PH3144)
Abstract
We have built a Frequency detector that can measure the frequency of the loudest sound detected. The motiva-
tion for this project was to create something useful for our lab. We have kept the entire circuitry of the device
simple and took the help of the Fast Fourier Transform to show the frequency of the input sound intensity on
a 10-bit LED display. The sensor accuracy is high enough; thanks to the manufactural sanity, we can measure
the frequency to an accuracy of 99% or above.
1 Introduction
1.1 Components used
1. Arduino Nano
The Arduino Nano is a small, complete, and breadboard-friendly board based on the ATmega328P re-
leased in 2008. The Arduino Nano is equipped with 30 male I/O headers in a DIP-30-like conﬁguration,
which can be programmed using the Arduino Software integrated development environment (IDE), which
is common to all Arduino boards and runs both online and oﬄine.
The board can be powered by a type-B mini-USB cable or a 9 V battery. It has a ﬂash memory of
32 KB, and the bootloader uses 2 KB. It has an SRAM of 2 KB, EEPROM of 1KB and a clock speed of
16 MHz
2. Breadboard
A modern solderless breadboard socket consists of a perforated block of plastic with numerous tin-plated
phosphor bronze or nickel-silver alloy spring clips under the perforations. The clips are often called tie
points or contact points. The number of tie points is often given in the speciﬁcation of the breadboard.
3. Light emitting diode(LED)
A light-emitting diode (LED) is a semiconductor device that emits light when current ﬂows through it.
Electrons in the semiconductor recombine with electron holes, releasing energy in the form of photons.
The color of the light (corresponding to the energy of the photons) is determined by the energy re-
quired for electrons to cross the band gap of the semiconductor. White light is obtained using multiple
semiconductors or a light-emitting phosphor layer on the semiconductor device.
4. Push button switch
A push-button or simply button is a simple switch mechanism to control some aspect of a machine or a
process. Buttons are typically made out of hard material, usually plastic or metal. The surface is usually
ﬂat or shaped to accommodate the human ﬁnger or hand to be easily depressed or pushed. Buttons are
often biased switches, although many unbiased buttons (due to their physical nature) still require a spring
to return to their un-pushed state.
5. Big sound sensor (HW-484 v0.2)
This sensor can detect sound and outputs both an analog signal and a digital signal that can be used to
create a clap-on/clap-oﬀ light switch. This sensor is very useful with the relay module. The sensor also
has a built-in potentiometer that can be used to set the threshold for digital output.

2.3 Working principle
For this project, the measured frequency is displayed using the 10-bit LED system. The white LED indicates
the power-on state of the system. The sound module detector is turned on whenever the push button switch is
pressed. The analog output from the sound module detector sends the analog audio signal detected to A0 of
the Arduino Nano. The analog signal is sampled and quantized (digitized). A Fast Fourier Transform (FFT) is
then performed on the digitized data. The FFT converts the digital data from the approximate discrete-time
domain result. The maximum frequency of the approximate discrete-time domain result is then determined and
displayed using the 10-bit LED display system.
2.3.1 Digitization
The output after the Fourier transform is rounded oﬀ to the closest integer value. Then, this value is converted
to 10-bit binary code by the binary converter, continuously dividing it by increasing powers of 2 and checking
for remainders to be higher than some ﬁxed value. The binary code is then displayed in the LED display. The
true output of the Fourier transform can be seen on the serial monitor of Arduino IDE.

3 Conclusion
• According to table 1, we can conclude that our Arduino project is a success. The software and hardware
are working perfectly in sync.
• The device detects frequencies between 1Hz to 1KHz as long as the sound intensity is audible enough
for the sound sensor.
• Thus within the detectable range we can use this device to detect the frequencies produced by a body in
our labs. We can use it to label the frequency a tuning fork to a high degree of accuracy.
